metadata.title: Cessna 150
aws::graph::propositions: Reims Aviation produced 1,764 Cessna 150 aircraft under license in France.
French manufactured Cessna 150s were designated Reims F150 or Reims-Cessna F150.
The "F" in Reims F150 and Reims-Cessna F150 indicated the aircraft were built in France.
American-made Cessna 150s were all produced with the Continental O-200-A engine.
The Continental O-200-A engine provided 100 horsepower (75 kW).
Most Reims-built Cessna 150 aircraft are powered by a Continental O-200-A built under license by Rolls-Royce.
Some Reims-built Cessna 150 aircraft have the Rolls-Royce-built version of the Continental O-240-A.
All Cessna 150 models from 1966 onwards have larger doors.
All Cessna 150 models from 1966 onwards have increased baggage space.
With the 1967 Model 150G, the doors were bowed outwards 1.5 inches (38 mm) on each side.
The bowed doors on the 1967 Model 150G provided more cabin elbow room.
The Cessna 150 was succeeded by the closely related Cessna 152 in the summer of 1977.

text:
1,764 aircraft were also produced by Reims Aviation under license in France. These French manufactured 150s were designated Reims F150 or Reims-Cessna F150, the "F" indicating they were built in France.
American-made 150s were all produced with the Continental O-200-A engine of 100 horsepower (75 kW). Most Reims-built aircraft are powered by a Continental O-200-A built under license by Rolls-Royce, but some have the Rolls-Royce-built version of the Continental O-240-A.
All models from 1966 onwards have larger doors and increased baggage space. With the 1967 Model 150G, the doors were bowed outwards 1.5 inches (38 mm) on each side to provide more cabin elbow room.
The 150 was succeeded in the summer of 1977 by the closely related Cessna 152.
